Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. The Claimant Count in September 2022 was 31.3% higher than in January 2020. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 3.1% in September 2022 representing an increment of 0.8% from January 2020. The number of claimants has been decreasing from April 2021.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in September 2022 was Clifford with 12.3% of all claimants within Trafford. All the wards have less claims in September 2022 compared to September 2021. Longford have the largest reduction in number of claims with (-135) followed by Clifford (-130), Bucklow-St Martins (-125) and Gorse Hill (-105).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in September 2022 were Clifford and Bucklow-St Martins with 6.3% and 5.7% respectively. There is a gap of 1.5% between the top five wards on claimant rate and the rest of the wards. The wards where the claimant rate has decreased more from September 2021 to September 2022 are Bucklow-St Martins and Longford with a decrease in rate of -2.1% and -1.6% respectively followed by Clifford with -1.5 and Gorse Hill with -1.3%.

In Trafford from September 2021 to September 2022 all age bands have reduced their claimant count. When considering the reduction of claims the age band 18-24 years had the largest reduction with -335 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Trafford’s population within each age band shows a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others. The rate and count have been decreasing during the last months for all age bands particularly for the the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34.

Almost half of Trafford’s claimants are residents of five of the 21 wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 34 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 79.2% from January 2020 to September 2022. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 11%.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in September 2022 was Old Trafford with 11.9% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. 30% of the MSOAs have more claims in September 2022 compared to September 2021. The MSOAs with more additional in claims when comparing September 2021 to September 2022 were Gorse Hill (39), Partington (38) and Altrincham West, Dunham & Warburton (25). The MSOA with more increase in percentage change from September 2021 to September 2022 was Altrincham West, Dunham & Warburton with 7% change. The MSOAs with more reduction in claims when comparing September 2021 to September 2022 are Firswood (-72), Ashton upon Mersey North (-52) and Sale Central (-45). The MSOA with more reduction in percentage change from September 2021 to September 2022 was Ashton upon Mersey South with -19% change.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in September 2022 were Partington with 27.4% and Old Trafford with 24%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has increased more from September 2021 to September 2022 were Partington with 0.7% and Gorse Hill with 0.6%. The MSOA where the rate of Universal Credit claims has decreased more from September 2021 to September 2022 was Ashton upon Mersey North with -1.3%

In Trafford from September 2021 to September 2022 the Over 65 age band has the largest increment in percentage change of Universal Credit claims with 53%. When considering the number of additional claims from September 2021 to September 2022 the 5-year age band 35-39 years had the highest with 166 more claims. The age bands 20-24 and 25-29 have the largest decrease in number of Universal Credit claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from March 2020 until May 2022 when the 35-44 became the age band with the highest number of claims. The age band 16-24 has the lowest number of claims among the other age bands from July 2021. All the age bands but the 16-24 are increasing their number of claims particularly the age bands 25-34 and 35-44 from June 2022.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the “Searching for Work” category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under “No work requirements”.
